name: Anonymous
com:
Go /p/ro:
• Please post images that are JPG format and ideally smaller than 1 MB, and/or about 1000 pixels on the longest side.
• Expect to be judged harshly. Learn to deal with it.

Want:
• We come here for photos, so post yours as often as possible, even if "image unrelated" to your text.
• "Flickr/500px/Tumblr/Facebook/Portfolio" threads are for critique and networking.
• Use "Recent Photos" threads if you are shy or only want to post a couple of photos.
• Shared raw files which we can collectively edit for discussion of post-processing techniques, are encouraged.
• Use the Catalog to consolidate similar topics (photographic themes, images or technical gear threads).

Do not want:
• Go to /wsr/ or /r/ for specific Photoshop requests.
• Gear threads are discouraged, but identified as necessary. Many users simply hide these threads.

Want to learn more?
• The /p/ Wiki

[{'no': 4111095, 'now': '12/12/22(Mon)15:26:02', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': 'photobooks are stupid.
the limitations of pages necessarily having to bend and therefore introduce distortions into the image, as well as be a reasonable size, are not necessary to deal with in the modern day.
a color calibrated monitor is a far, far better tool for consuming photography.
if only photographers were more keen on adapting pdfs as a distribution format.', 'time': 1670876762, 'resto': 4108719}, {'no': 4111114, 'now': '12/12/22(Mon)16:13:36', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>4110762
paper movies', 'time': 1670879616, 'resto': 4108719}, {'no': 4111244, 'now': '12/12/22(Mon)22:25:59', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>4111095
Top retard take. You could not monetize pdf's, besides they are substandard medium regarding images.', 'time': 1670901959, 'resto': 4108719}, {'no': 4111258, 'now': '12/12/22(Mon)23:18:18', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>4111244
>they are substandard medium regarding images
why? give actual reasons, don't just make statements.', 'time': 1670905098, 'resto': 4108719}, {'no': 4111346, 'now': '12/13/22(Tue)06:44:26', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>4111095
Have you ever come close to a fine art photo print? The texture of the paper, the specific colors resulting from a specific time consuming process, the lighting, it all adds a lot to how you feel the picture.
You're looking at a piece of art, you want to present it in conditions that sublimate the piece, not make for a technically optimal viewing experience. I bet you're the kind to obsess over sensor size, lens sharpness and specs etc.
If that's the kind of stuff you enjoy, good for you. But please, go to a photo expo, look at some nice grainy, unsharp, abstract pictures, get yourself a nice fine art print or photo book, and just enjoy it.', 'time': 1670931866, 'resto': 4108719}]

name: Anonymous
sub: How the fuck does depth of field work at f1.4
com:
I recently bought an 85mm f1.4 and used it for the first time today at a cosplay event. The event was indoors so lighting wasn't great and I shot wide open at f1.4. The camera set shutter speed to 1/125 and iso anywhere from 100-400.
Question 1:
For most of my pictures, I was far enough away from the cosplayer(s) to get their heads down to roughly their thighs in frame and manually set the focus point to one of their eyes. Photos looked sharp on the screen but when I zoomed in I noticed that their body was slightly of focus. This is due to very shallow DoF right? Is there any way around this other than stopping down?
Question 2:
When I took pictures of 2 or more cosplayers standing right next to each other at f1.4, I wasn't able to get both in focus. I could see very clearly on the screen that only 1 face was in focus, despite them standing basically next right to each other. Why is this?
last_replies:
[{'no': 4111123, 'now': '12/12/22(Mon)16:29:36', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>4111105
>looking perfectly normal
That's normal to you? This is theatre. They are describing nothing that isn't in theatre. You're just wrong.

Cinema is theatre being captured on camera. A photographer running that camera can add something much more, because a photograph is a song in itself. And photographers do more than just capture images. They do more than direct subjects, and don't have to be the ones direction the subjects to begin with. They also... EDIT THEM.

> Cinema is first and foremost a visual art. A picture can be good despite the actors, sound design and script being terrible but there's no saving one with weak photography.
Do you have any idea how common it is for films to have dogshit photography that amounts to "point a camera over there, make sure everything on the set is in focus, start it, now HOLD STILL? >This is theatre. They are describing nothing that isn't in theatre. You're just wrong.

Are you kidding? Do you even have an idea of who those directors were? Have you even seen Olympia or Triumph des Willens? Riefenstahl had no control over her subjects, but she had all the control in the world over the picture.
Static shots and bad cinematography aren't the same thing. And no, it's not common at all to have one shot for the entire movie. The filmed plays as you described are forgotten because of what I said, there's no saving a film with bad photography.
Photographers direct subjects all the time, just look at any photographer who does people photography and is more than a snapper. Sometimes the direction is as simple as "say cheese". Acting in cinema is just modeling in motion, specially when we're talking about silent film. But it's true, sometimes photographers don't direct their subjects, as seen with Riefenstahl. She just controlled the picture itself, she MADE the photographs. Sometimes their subjects aren't even alive. Take "10 Skies", for example. That is distilled cinema, absolute kinography, bare photography. There's no actors, the star is the sky. There's no music either. Read my quote again. There's no saving those "movies".

This simply isn't true. The colors are mostly different due to camera input profiles bundled with these cameras, not the differences between thin vs thick CFA. Thick CFAs are also no closer to film than thin CFAs due to film using subtractive vs additive color systems(Additive systems are superior in basically everyway, and can simulate the look of film no prob).
>he drive behind the popularity of old ccd cameras today isn't just the colors. Its the sensors sensors themselves capture light differently. The pixels are larger than today's cameras.
Large vs small pixels doesn't matter, if you control for light capture/area is more important and basically the same for the same sensor tech.
Since shot noise dominates at high iso, high iso will be grainy no matter what. However, read noise is basically all the noise in low iso use case, since there is virtually no shot noise. CCD has way worse read noise at any iso compared with CMOS and the same size sensor. Read noise is not nice, it isn't pleasant like film grain or shot noise, its blotchy and irregular. CCD and CMOS are basically the same, except CCD is worse in basically all applications.
While the 'experience' of using a camera might matter to some, I just want a camera that works well. The 'unique aesthetic' different shitty CCD cameras have can be made with basic contrast and color adjustments, cropping, and adding digital noise in post.
While to past certainly has 'sleeper' cameras that punch above their price used. These old CCD cameras aren't them.

name: Anonymous
com:
Crushed dreams and lost hope Edition
All video related questions and discussion is intended for this thread. Here we discuss techniques, gear and anything else related to capturing video footage. Please don't pretend to be an expert if you don't know what you're talking about. Kindly leave your ego at the door.
Posting short films/scripts or other work you've done is encouraged.
We tend to use and recommend DSLRs/mirrorless cameras because they provide phenomenal picture quality for their price, have large sensors (ie the same size used in high-end cinema cameras and higher) and have interchangeable lenses.
In contrast, consumer camcorders normally have much smaller sensors and a fixed lens.

>STICKY -https://textbin.net/2u146abxla
>Helpful guide, additional books and more in-depth FAQs - https://web.archive.org/web/20200926115310/https://pastebin.com/kG0gRmTZ

>NO ONE CARES WHAT AN EXPERT YOU THINK YOU ARE. IF YOU’RE ASKING BASIC-AS-SHIT QUESTIONS, YOU CAN’T BE ALL THAT GREAT. SEE ABOVE

Previous thread >>4095075

Quick FAQS
>what’s the best camera available on a “budget”?
The blackmagic pocket cinema camera 4k
>>what’s a good beginner video camera?
Anything that works, shoots at least 1080p and preferably has interchangeable lenses. Any recommendation beyond that will cause arguments so read the fucking sticky if that isn't satisfactory.
>Can I use a zoom lens for video?
Yes
>Do I need cine lenses?
No
>Do I need 4k?
No. It will make your footage look sharper if it’s in focus, and it gives you breathing room in post. But 1080p is still absolutely fine
>Can someone tell me if my video is any good?

[{'no': 4110795, 'now': '12/11/22(Sun)20:14:35', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>4110787
Usually around 2 AM, I put on the album Morrison Hotel by The Doors, and rig up my a6000/90mm 2.8 to the back of a chair using a flexible mini tripod. The camera is pointing straight down, towards a clear glass dish filled with water/cooking oil. "Peace Frog" is praised among the album's best tunes; Louder Sound ranked the song among "The Top 20 Greatest Doors Songs", and I think I agree.
I’ve cut a circular hole just smaller than the diameter of the dish into the top of a cardboard box, and place the dish in the hole. The brim of the dish prevents it from sipping through. Into the side of the box, at the bottom, I’ve cut a slot. It’s through this slot that I slide an iPad under the dish. On YouTube there’s hours long videos of swirling/shifting colors, this illuminates the dish from below. Doing this in the dark intensifies the brightness.
Did you know Alice Cooper claimed that he was the inspiration for the line "Woke up this morning and I got myself a beer"? He said that on his podcast.
The oil droplets move around pretty quickly in the dish, so a higher shutter speed is helpful in getting clear shots. I usually cover the dish if I’m changing batteries or YouTube videos, this prevents dust from landing in the water.Focus the lens, and take a swig of rum from the bottle, and take some pictures.
Afterwards, upload them to photoshop/Lightroom or whatever and correct for exposure levels/contrast

name: cinefag
com: I'm currently considering the plot outline for a future project, about a photographer who basically behaves like a walking CCTV camera. It starts with him genuinely wanting to be a good photographer, but he realizes he's talentless so he starts taking photos rather than making them, in hopes of getting something good. He does a couple times, but his luck starts drying out and deep down he knows he's a fraud hack who couldn't create a compelling picture if his life depended on it. He gets desperate, starts shooting dozens of rolls per day. Often doesn't bother developing them. The madness starts to consume him and his marriage is shattered. That only makes things worse, he needs the click of that shutter like a junkie needs a hit. More and more pics, gambles, but he's not winning any rounds. Eventually all the worry gives him bladder cancer. Jump cut, he's dead and there's thousands of rolls of undeveloped film at his home. All for nothing, most of those pictures will never be seen by anyone (and it's a good thing, because there's nothing worth looking at in most of them). Working title: Cellulloid Madness.

com:
Does it makes sense to get any other camera than a Hasselblad 500 series nowadays?

I have a TLR and I was looking at Mamiyas and Bronicas for something more modern but still affordable, but at this point a lot of them are now sold close to or at Hassie prices, and in some cases more. Does it even make sense getting those anymore? Especially given that a lot of these cameras are electronic and may shit the bed any time, whereas repair shops that can service Hasselblads will probably be around for a very long time.

Unsolicited advice:

Unless you can take the filter off the sensor yourself for free that's probably not the best body to turn into an IR camera. It costs $175-300 to get it done, that's a lot money to put into a camera that's not worth half that. The optical autofocusing won't work either with infrared unless it's specifically tuned for a single lens. If that body can live view autofocus then you can just do that, but you can't focus in the viewfinder then.

Canon M50s or M5s are pretty cheap these days, and you don't have to deal with any of that ir autofocus bullshit then.

There's a list somewhere of lenses that done flare up like crazy from the IR reflecting back and forth between the elements, and I'm pretty sure most EF-M lenses are A-OK, also. Including the 22mm and the 18-55mm, which are cheap and pretty good. Might be worth double checking that though.', 'time': 1670707020, 'resto': 4101402}, {'no': 4110600, 'now': '12/11/22(Sun)12:23:30', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>4110370
M50 is pretty underrated imo. i think theyre known so widely as the "youtube vlogger video camera" that they dont get talked about for photography much, but i love shooting with mine.', 'time': 1670779410, 'resto': 4101402}, {'no': 4110705, 'now': '12/11/22(Sun)16:12:47', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>4110600
My only complaint about them is the lack of a second wheel or dial. Having to press record to switch between the two modes for the single dial is lame. Most sub-pro tier canons stick you with shit like that though, so it's not unusual. I really wish they would have stuck an expose comp dial on there too like the M5, though.

Other than that it's a genuinely excellent camera.', 'time': 1670793167, 'resto': 4101402}]

name: Anonymous
com:
CCD benefits

Can anybody explain what are the benefits of CCD versus CMOS?

I heard something about the sensor's layer composition that helps getting good sharpness with old lenses, as being closer to how film performs in the focal plane rendering.
last_replies:
[{'no': 4110587, 'now': '12/11/22(Sun)12:07:38', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>4100265
this man gets it. you're all retarded', 'time': 1670778458, 'resto': 4099851}, {'no': 4110588, 'now': '12/11/22(Sun)12:08:42', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>4100530
i own the m9 and it's the same as the m8 and you're an absolute troll', 'time': 1670778522, 'resto': 4099851}, {'no': 4110589, 'now': '12/11/22(Sun)12:09:17', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>4100530
it's extremely easy to clip the highlights with those cameras. many people will shoot two stops underexposed because of this.', 'time': 1670778557, 'resto': 4099851}, {'no': 4110596, 'now': '12/11/22(Sun)12:15:33', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': 'why scanners still use CCD sensor', 'filename': 'F27F08DA-470D-443B-8D6A-0031B957F491', 'ext': '.png', 'w': 527, 'h': 388, 'tn_w': 125, 'tn_h': 92, 'tim': 1670778933432010, 'time': 1670778933, 'md5': 'riGtAfRUxH8Q7VcKeUUnag==', 'fsize': 477310, 'resto': 4099851}, {'no': 4110645, 'now': '12/11/22(Sun)14:13:12', 'name': 'Art_repro_fag22', 'com': '>>4109764
You can get the 'ccd look' with edits to modern cmos raw of the same sensor size. Shooting an old MF digital back would be a cheap way to get to get mf look, probably even cheaper than film in the long run. That was my point from the beginning. Modern FF cmos is going better in basically everyway.
>>4110266
This is all wrong. While CCD cameras are often bundled with camera profiles that look like slide film, any camera can be profiled or edited to look like slides. This is bc slide film uses subtractive colors, and is worse for both color accuracy and gamut, even with perfect dyes. Modern slide film has a gamut smaller than 80's CRT tv.
>inb4 source
The reproduction of color, Hunt, ch. 2-5.
Foveon has the potential to be 'more digital' (which I take to be colorimetric) than bayer or xtrans, but the software support is quite bad at the moment. I'm very excited for the new FF foveon sensor from sigma coming out next year tho.
>>4110552
>>4110563
These honestly both look digital me. They could both be edited to look like slide film if that was your goal.
>>4110596
Scanners all use CCD bc scanning tech is stuck in the early 2000's. This is mostly due to lack of money in the industry. Using a film scanner is probably the worst/slowest way to digitalize film, best would obviously be gfx100s with 16 shot pixel shift and sharp macro lens on a copy stand setup.', 'time': 1670785992, 'resto': 4099851}]

there are two kinds of people in photography: photographers, and AV technicians.
the photographers can double as AV technicians, but the AV technicians rarely double as photographers. you can tell the difference because a photographer doing technician duty immediately frames everything as it affects the act of photography and puts everything else second, while the technician compares fine details that are wholly irrelevant to the work of art and does not pay any mind to immediate function, ergonomics, etc. as a practical example, a photographer delving into technicals will notice something like battery life, autofocus, size and weight, or lens compatibility. a true AV nerd writes a giant nonsensical essay about 3% extra shot noise in the dark red spectrum.', 'time': 1670617192, 'resto': 4109430}, {'no': 4110171, 'now': '12/10/22(Sat)03:23:07', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>4109430

name: cinefag
com:
Griffith and Eisenstein aggressively turn you off because of their layered expression which many deem to be "camp." Bresson stripped these layers, and even stripped the very metaphysical and dialectical nature of Flaherty's work to replace with literary adaptation.

To be true to life, you must exceed good taste. Cinephiles crave literature, cinephiles crave music, cinephiles crave visual entertainment. Where high art necessarily incorporates beauty and value, camp necessarily needs to be lively, audacious and dynamic. Camp aesthetics delights in impertinence. Camp opposes satisfaction and seeks to challenge. To divorce from immediate reality and metaphysically imprint, to pierce reality with reality and assess fully.

name: Anonymous
com:
Photography is almost inherently tied to travel and socialization. You can only take so many photos in a single location of certain people before it gets dull and the difficulty of doing something creative and fresh increases exponentially. You can start moving things around, compiling sequences (very low frame rate movies), working with the lights, but with visuals you can only do so much. Leaving the house is almost required because it is the easiest way to find new ways to be creative. Keeping it fresh while staying home is genuinely impressive. People staying home sometimes devolve into gearfags because changing equipment is one of the easiest ways to change your photos.

A movie with sound, however, can milk the same house, 3 people, and pet cat almost infinitely with nothing but an iphone and some ideas much more effortlessly because narration and constant movement increase the amount of variety that is immediately accessible. The possibilities of language (including body language) and music are infinite compared to a human lifetime.

For this reason I believe shut in autists will gravitate towards cinema while still photography is more of a grass-toucher's thing. Appreciating cinema also passes more time. Great for someone stuck in a basement with nothing but time.

name: Anonymous
com:
Talk about something you get autistic over in photography.
I'll start.

I've followed this advice since the start of time, if I am to shoot handheld and there's not enough light, and my camera has let's say a 50mm lens on. My lowest acceptable shutter speed should be 1/50s. In practice if I hold very very steady I can maybe go to 1/30s and still get an acceptable image.
Now. If on crop sensors, because of the crop factor, a 33mm lens is equivalent to a 50mm while letting me shoot with a 1/30s all the while getting a good image would mean technically that it is better at low light photography, excluding noise and desired photo characteristics.
But... Larger sensors have less noise, which sort of balances the need for a theoretically higher acceptable shutter speed. But to what extent?
Also, if a camera has sensor stabilization, how far can I push my acceptable shutter speed below the normal acceptable speed? 1 stop? 2 stops?
Looking at the tiny amount of data regarding this online (maybe because most photographers are not this autistic), I'm starting to think that a newer, less noisy, image stabilized APS-C camera might reign supreme in terms of low light handheld shooting.

Preferably I'd spend less though', 'time': 1670380110, 'resto': 4108497}, {'no': 4108531, 'now': '12/06/22(Tue)21:51:40', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>4108519
Not a bad budget, if you sold your current camera body, you could easily get a used Canon 70d off of your version of eBay. It would be a huge upgrade in terms of camera features. It definitely has more tools to help you take the photos you want.

Here's the thing though, in terms of image quality, it's not going to be a huge step up. Your old ass rebel 1000d still takes good photos. Especially in this day and age of viewing said images online. scaled down and viewed on your phone via instagram or facebook. Even on a monitor if zoomed out. you're going to be hard pressed to tell what camera took what photo.

The biggest and best upgrade you can do is USUALLY better lenses. Can I ask what lens/lenses you currently have? There's solid budget options available there too.

With how old your body is, I actually still think it'd be an alright idea to upgrade, but being as new as you are, you still haven't learned to make the most out of your 1000d.

So imo here are you options. Grab the canon 70d. Or perhaps grab something like the canon T3i/600d with a nice lens like the 50mm f.18 STM lens. Or the 55-250mm STM lens.', 'time': 1670381500, 'resto': 4108497}, {'no': 4108558, 'now': '12/06/22(Tue)23:20:03', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>4108531

So I could definitely look at some other lenses that might do me better than just picking up a better camera body

>>4107610
isn't backblaze poorly desgined for photo backups? from what i've seen you can only backup a folder and retrieve them, but there's no way to actually see them from the web. part of the charm of smugmug is that it also serves as a gallery for your backed photos, but not so sure with backblaze', 'time': 1670171177, 'resto': 4107551}, {'no': 4107712, 'now': '12/04/22(Sun)15:24:52', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>4107619
it's poorly designed because it doesn't fit your specific wants? backblaze does what it's supposed to do: backs up your entire computer and any attached external drives. it's not a photo gallery.', 'time': 1670185492, 'resto': 4107551}, {'no': 4107917, 'now': '12/05/22(Mon)08:50:26', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': 'During editing I copy them from the SD card to my PC; at least they're in 2 locations at that point (although still just one physical location, which isn't great).

Once I'm finished editing, I store them locally on my Synology DS920+, and the Lightroom catalog and settings backups are there as well. The NAS syncs with backblaze and I also back it up weekly to a drive in a USB enclosure that's otherwise disconnected from the NAS and power when not backing up.

I also backup the photos to Amazon since I have prime anyway and it's unlimited including RAW files.

With this method I should be covered for local or remote disasters, as well as ransomware.

I use Flickr for my online gallery but my Pro plan renews in a few weeks and it's another big price increase this year. Sucks but that's where all my community is.', 'time': 1670248226, 'resto': 4107551}]

sub: Is the Cannon EOS Rebel T7 any good?
com:
I have been looking at cameras online and in store this week, I've been pretty into photography this year and want to move on from just using my mobile phone.
I mostly do still life and landscape photos, typically nature and travel, with some street photography.
What are your thoughts on the Canon EOS Rebel T7? It seems pretty solid to me, and it is in my price range, but I wanted to ask some more experienced in the field whether this was good for me, or if there are any others that they would recomme
last_replies:
[{'no': 4106938, 'now': '12/02/22(Fri)16:33:30', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>4106392
For the price of a d5300, OP could get an original Olympus E-M1. For that money you get a pro grade, metal body with excellent weather sealing and 5 axis image stabilization. Plus a a lot of other features. Then OP could pair that with the cheap, but competent Zuiko 12-50mm lens. It's not a fast lens, but it's also weather sealed, well built, can sort of do macro and has good sharpness. There's several cheap, fast primes available too.', 'time': 1670016810, 'resto': 4106336}, {'no': 4106946, 'now': '12/02/22(Fri)16:59:43', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>4106392
>The T7 has an ancient sensor with less dynamic range than a Nikon D5100 from 2011 meaning low light will suck if you want to push shadows.
It has the 80D sensor and is fine with a 4ev push at base ISO. Which is about the same for the D5100. In low light / high ISO all cameras converge to nearly the same DR as they are bound more by the low light and less by the sensor.

In terms of high ISO noise it's a little bit behind the best sensors available today, maybe 2/3ev and probably about the same as old Nikons.

That said I do agree anon is better off with a used 80D than a new T7 because of the body ergonomics and features.

>I'd buy at minimum something like a T3i even if used. The usefulness of the articulated screen can't be understated.
The T3i has the much older 18mp sensor which does really lag behind current sensors in base ISO DR and high ISO performance.', 'time': 1670018383, 'resto': 4106336}, {'no': 4106951, 'now': '12/02/22(Fri)17:14:46', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>4106392
Also, as far as I can tell, the T7 does have a center pin and works with any flash. Amazon sells it in kits with 3rd party flashes, and photos from the top clearly show the center pin.', 'time': 1670019286, 'resto': 4106336}, {'no': 4107023, 'now': '12/02/22(Fri)21:28:54', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>4106951

There are 2 different models of T7. The first version didn't come with the center pin, whereas the "T7+" version had it.

Real imbecile move from Canon, as per usual.', 'time': 1670034534, 'resto': 4106336}, {'no': 4107031, 'now': '12/02/22(Fri)21:45:44', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>4107023
That is fucked.', 'time': 1670035544, 'resto': 4106336}]
